<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-144-652  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 144 652.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  March 27 1989 v23 n13 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Loophole lets states copy without risk. (copyright laws)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Betts, Mitch.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In response to the Supreme Court's decision to let stand alower-court ruling in BV Engineering v. University of Californiaat Los Angeles, the software industry seeks Congress' help inclosing a legal loophole that makes state-run institutions immunefrom copyright-infringement lawsuits.andP;  The legal implications stemfrom the 11th Amendment to the Constitution, which has astate-immunity clause.andP;  There are bills in the House and Senatethat make states subject to copyright-infringement suits.andP;  Thebills are part of an effort to deter widespread, uncontrollablecopying of computer programs.andP;  The Software PublishingAssociation, ADAPSO and the US Copyright Office support thelegislation, which is unopposed so far.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Supreme CourtCopyrightLegislationSoftware PackagesUnited States. Congress.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>